= lesson 28: moo!

Just one more important word to learn, before we get to the silly part!

#list((
  word("REPLACE", "taso", "but, only"),
))

#strong[󱥨 taso] can be a normal adjective meaning "only", but it can also be put
at the beginning of a sentence to mean "but".

#list((
  sentence("REPLACE", "mi taso li sona e ni.", "Only I am aware of this."),
  sentence("REPLACE", "mi awen wan taso.", "I remain alone."),
  sentence("REPLACE", "taso mi awen pilin pona.", "But I keep my spirits up."),
))

== The silly!

#strong[󱦆 n] is an interjection just like #strong[󱤀 a], but nasally:

#list((
  word("REPLACE", "n", "hmm, umm"),
  sentence("REPLACE", "n... mi sona ala.", "ummm... I don't know."),
))

#strong[󱤹 mu] is the kind of sound an animal makes! Which animal? Well, any of
them:

#list((
  word("REPLACE", "mu", "moo, meow, woof, neigh..."),
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "soweli mute! mu mu mu mu mu mu.",
    "Six cows! <a target='_blank' href='https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xxClPfZDn-E'>Moo moo moo moo moo moo</a>.",
  ),
))

People often use #strong[󱤹 mu] for silly reasons, but it has got genuine uses
too. If #strong[󱤕 kalama] is a #emph[description] of a sound, then #strong[󱤹 mu]
is an #emph[imitation] of a sound:

#list((
  sentence("REPLACE", "mi kute e kalama suli.", "I heard a loud noise."),
  sentence("REPLACE", "mi kute e mu suli.", "I heard a loud bang."),
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "ike la ilo li awen mu e mi.",
    "Unfortunately, the app keeps pinging me.",
  ),
))

== More words?

We have looked over all the words you #emph[need] to speak the language. But
people use slightly more words than that. Why? Because words aren't always about
the most efficient design. They are also about having fun. And perhaps no word
encapsulates having fun more than this one:

#list((
  word(
    "REPLACE",
    "kijetesantakalu",
    "raccoon; raccoon-like animal, like a cacomistle, red panda, kinkajou",
  ),
))

It's so long! And so specific! This is because it's an April fools joke
from 2009. But people remembered it many years later, and loved it! It has
become a bit of a mascot.

These two words also require a history note:

#list((
  word(
    "REPLACE",
    "pu",
    "(to interact with) <i>Toki Pona: The Language of Good (2014)</i>, by Sonja Lang",
  ),
  word(
    "REPLACE",
    "ku",
    "(to interact with) <i>Toki Pona Dictionary (2021)</i>, by Sonja Lang",
  ),
))

These words refer specifically to books made by #link(
  "https://tokipona.org/",
)[Sonja Lang], the creator of Toki Pona. Why do they have specialised words?
Maybe because they're funny. Maybe because people love to talk about what's in
the books, and what's not in the books --- so these words come in handy.

If you join a Toki Pona community, you will almost certainly see more words.
When you do, think of them as #emph[cultural artefacts]. They exist not to make
the language work --- you've seen all about how it works now! --- but rather to
experiment, to have fun, to be creative, to make in-jokes.

#list((
  sentence(
    "REPLACE",
    "kijetesantakalu tonsi li lanpan ala lanpan e soko?",
    "Does the non-binary raccoon steal mushrooms?",
  ),
))

You might not know the word #strong[󱦅 lanpan], but you can see the translation,
and you know enough by now to think of a suitable replacement in common words
(#strong[󱤖󱤓 kama jo])! It's much the same for other words you might see in the
wild.

